  "text": "On October 24, 1995 a total solar eclipse occurred with its path cutting through the low latitude region of Asia. [CITATION_1] used fl2 data measured from six ionosonde stations near the 120°E longitude chain, while [CITATION_2] used TEC data (using the tomographical reconstruction technique) at a chain of six NNSS receiving stations to study the response of the ionosphere to this solar eclipse. Some interesting effects were reported. For example, the largest depression in Nrnax occurred about 1.5 hours after the maximum obscura tion appeared near 14°N geomagnetic latitude even though the percent obscuration of the sun at lower latitudes was larger. About six hours after the maximum phase, another secondary depression in N was observed for latitudes lower than 14°N [CITATION_3] .",
